{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"67b37986-936d-4e7d-a6b6-3b6e3d2f656a","content":"There's no repository-specific documentation on this topic, so here's general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump`. On macOS, use the OS-native mechanisms:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Run your app** — when it crashes, macOS writes a core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check `/cores/`** for the dump:\n   ```bash\n   ls -la /cores/\n   ```\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is missing or empty**, ensure SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking it and that the directory exists with correct permissions:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **macOS Crash Reports** — Apple also writes `.ips` crash logs to `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`. These contain stack traces and can be a quick alternative to a full core dump.\n\n> **Tip:** On macOS 12+, `apple crash reports` (`.ips` JSON files) are often the easiest starting point before diving into a full core dump with `lldb`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"700e52c4-7529-4f61-8634-9baa38e6abe7","outputTokens":350,"requestId":"D806:149B26:FD835F:1230B9D:69F2B5A0"},"id":"6f961a0a-7a28-4b52-811f-e64e270a384b","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:51:39.255Z","parentId":"31cf33b0-e272-438b-8e6c-eef41efb9fa3"}
